post_text:
Ashley Sarno received The Sixth Annual Loretta McCormick Award for CROP this year.

Loretta McCormick was a dedicated and inspiring leader of the Creating Rural Opportunities Partnership (CROP). She was well known for her enthusiasm and commitment to the CROP Program. She worked tirelessly to see CROP realize its vision of excellence in the after-school program so that all students can learn, achieve, and have the confidence to succeed in our ever changing world. Ms. McCormick passed away in 2014. To honor her, three Loretta McCormick After-School Achievement Awards were created; one for an adult professional, a peer leader (student staff member), and a student participant.

Thank you to our parents for completing the survey. The results included 48.36% of parent respondents choosing a return to in-person instruction in the building with the new Department of Health and NYS Education Department mandates.
35.25% of parent respondents indicated a blend of in-person and remote instruction and the remaining 16.39% choosing remote instruction (like this spring).
We will be using this information in the planning needed to submit reopening plans to the NYS Education Department (on July 31). Dr Dengler and Mrs. Wright will hold a virtual Town Hall event early in the week of the 27th during the evening to share some of the details of the plan and gather additional feedback. This event will be open to all community members, parents, and students. Please check back for a posting with a link, date, and time.

post_text:
SKCS Class of 2020 Graduation will be on June 27 at 10am. ONLY ticketed guests will be allowed to attend. We have a very limited number of tickets. ALL guests must wear masks and adhere to social distancing protocols. Please do not attend if you are feeling unwell or have any of the common symptoms of COVID-19 (fever, chills, cough, shortness of breath, headache, muscle or body aches, loss of taste and/or smell, congestion, runny nose and/or sore throat).

Graduates and families should arrive in one car when at all possible. Attendees will be stopped in the lot and asked to present tickets before being directed where to park. Anyone without tickets will not be permitted to park and will be asked to leave. Arrival times begin at 9:30am. All guests will use the paved walkway from the parking lot behind the school to access the field where the ceremony will be held under a tent.

Some Updates:
Thank you to our coaches who hosted a virtual Athletic Banquet.
There will be a virtual Academic Awards Ceremony for Juniors and Seniors June 24
*We will not be having K-10 awards. This was decided because many of our awards are supported by community individuals and businesses. I did not think it was appropriate at this time to ask for those donations. Our traditional awards will return next year.
Due to no in-person summer school allowed, we will not have summer driver education, summer school, or CROP.
We will have a modified in-person graduation limited to the graduate and parents scheduled in a sequence to avoid a gathering over 10 people. This will be a recorded event and sent to families.
The District has put together a re-opening leadership team that includes students. We have begun our planning.
If you have any questions please do not hesitate to email me at kdengler@skcs.org or call the school at 538-9111.
Stay safe and healthy.

post_text:
Whew! What a storm we had last night! The school property sustained some damage as a result. Attached are some photos. PLEASE do NOT drive on the property. We need to be able to clean this up first.

One set of bleachers (which were flung into the light pole), one girls dugout completely dismantled, a few pieces of slate off the roof (front and back), lots of downed trees on all perimeter areas (some onto neighboring property).

Lots of tree-related debris all over, items moved (like benches and the greenhouse). Some metal signs blown over as well.

We hope you are all safe and that any damage you received was minimal. Enjoy the nice weather this weekend!

post_text:
Mr. Wombacker presents...the Wommy Awards!

"Every year when the 7th grade learns about the War of 1812, we do a movie poster project because I teach them that it is a sequel to the Revolutionary War.

They are assigned to create a movie poster for the war using the idea of a sequel for a title (returns, again, back, more, two/too) and the best posters get a Wommy Award. (not as prestigious as an Oscar,but definitely better than a S.A.G. Award)."

Excellent work, 7th grade students!

post_text: Tuesday, April 14th buses will once again be delivering paper materials to students. They will leave the school at 3pm and travel the regular bus runs. If you are waiting at the stop, please stand back and let the adult leave your items on a mailbox, sidewalk, or some other spot. You may retrieve the items once the bus pulls away, please do not approach the adult at your stop. If you are waiting to cross the road, please do so with an adult present after the bus leaves watching carefully for vehicles. We will not be taking anything back with us, so please do not try to send items back. Out of district students must call the school to make arrangements for a pick up time.

Please get ready to participate in the 2020 Census!
Census results affect planning and funding for education‚Äîincluding programs such as Head Start, Pell Grants, school lunches, rural education, adult education, and grants for preschool special education.
By April 1, 2020, every home will receive an invitation to participate in the 2020 Census. You will have three options for responding:
Online.
By phone.
By mail.
In mid-March, households will begin receiving official Census Bureau mail with detailed information on how to respond to the 2020 Census.
The district will have computers available once online participation has begun. More information to come.
text:
Please get ready to participate in the 2020 Census!
Census results affect planning and funding for education‚Äîincluding programs such as Head Start, Pell Grants, school lunches, rural education, adult education, and grants for preschool special education.
By April 1, 2020, every home will receive an invitation to participate in the 2020 Census. You will have three options for responding:
Online.
By phone.
By mail.
In mid-March, households will begin receiving official Census Bureau mail with detailed information on how to respond to the 2020 Census.
The district will have computers available once online participation has begun. More information to come.

post_text: Dear Parents: This year, students in grades 3-8 will be given the NYS ELA assessment March 25-26. SK students will be taking these assessments on paper rather than on computer. There are many benefits to you, your child, and to the South Kortright School District, to having your child participate in these assessments. First and foremost, they provide valuable information to you and to our instructional staff about your child‚Äôs academic achievement. As a district, we then use this information to help us create a plan for instruction that meets the needs of all learners. By state law, student results on these assessments are no longer permitted to be used in evaluating teacher performance. Student achievement scores do not appear on a student‚Äôs transcript. We encourage you to have your child participate in these assessments. If you have any questions or concerns, please contact an administrator.
